<paper id="1551212655"><title>On Conservative Enforced Updates</title><year>1997</year><authors><author org="Tver State University" id="1271351648">Michael I. Dekhtyar</author><author org="Keldysh Institute for Applied Math." id="2143690299">Alexander Ja. Dikovsky</author><author org="Université de Paris — Sud" id="171306905">Nicolas Spyratos</author></authors><n_citation>6</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1496528554</reference><reference>1506952729</reference><reference>1519893275</reference><reference>1539290233</reference><reference>1593260998</reference><reference>1846779381</reference><reference>1968513265</reference><reference>1975442866</reference><reference>1982345710</reference><reference>1997526587</reference><reference>2007457223</reference><reference>2094341147</reference></references><venue id="1201110412" type="C">International Conference on Logic Programming</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-63255-7_19</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.0">Algorithm complexity</keyword><keyword weight="0.47962">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.57151">Oracle</keyword><keyword weight="0.45758">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.47554">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.59828">Data integrity</keyword><keyword weight="0.46975">Artificial intelligence</keyword><keyword weight="0.52843">Computational complexity theory</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A new method is proposed of restoring integrity constraints after committing an external update of a data base. This method is conservative in the sense that it performs the minimum of the necessary changes in the initial data base. The method is based on a novel idea of a so called preference strategy, i.e. an “oracle” which resolves globally all the conflicts, taking into account the update to be committed.</abstract></paper>